      • singleOrNull

        public static <T> T singleOrNull​(Iterator<T> iterator)
        Returns the given iterator's single element or null if no element found. If there is more than one element in the iterator a NoSuchElementException will be thrown. If the iterator implements Resource it will be closed in a finally block after the single item has been retrieved, or failed to be retrieved.
        Type Parameters:
        T - the type of elements in iterator.
        Parameters:
        iterator - the Iterator to get elements from.
        Returns:
        the single element in iterator, or null if no element found.
        Throws:
        NoSuchElementException - if more than one element was found.

      • loop

        public static <T> Iterable<T> loop​(Iterator<T> iterator)
        Convenience method for looping over an Iterator. Converts the Iterator to an Iterable by wrapping it in an Iterable that returns the Iterator. It breaks the contract of Iterable in that it returns the supplied iterator instance for each call to iterator() on the returned Iterable instance. This method exists to make it easy to use an Iterator in a for-loop.
        Type Parameters:
        T - the type of items in the iterator.
        Parameters:
        iterator - the iterator to expose as an Iterable.
        Returns:
        the supplied iterator posing as an Iterable.

        public static <T> String toString​(Iterator<T> iterator,
                                  Function<T,​String> toString,
                                  int maxItems)
        Produce a string of the form [A, B, C, ...] by consuming up to maxItems objects from the iterator, optionally appending an ellipsis if the iterator has more than maxItems in it.
        Type Parameters:
        T - the type of objects in the iterator.
        Parameters:
        iterator - the iterator to format as a string.
        toString - the function that converts the iterator elements to strings.
        maxItems - the maximum number of items to include in the string.
        Returns:
        a string of the form [A, B, C] or [A, B, C, ...].
